observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management direct the Municipal Accountant to:
Prepare monthly BRS for all the bank accounts of the LGU, and ensure that the BRS, together with the supporting documents (such as BS, original copies of DMs/CMs, and schedules), for the ensuing period/s will be submitted to the auditors to facilitate review and examination thereof;
Exert utmost effort in conducting a thorough review of Cash in Bank records through confirmation, validation, and verification of the reconciling items which were already identified and reflected in the BRS, and prepare the necessary correcting/adjusting entries to reflect the correct balance of the Cash-in-Bank-Local Currency, Current Account;
Communicate in writing the identified bank errors, including the long-standing deposits in transit, to the depository banks, and request that the respective account’s balance be corrected or updated;
Trace, analyze, and determine the causes for the unreconciled balance between the book and bank balances; and
Draw the necessary adjusting entries to revert back to the cash in bank balance the amounts of the stale checks.

We recommended that Management require the:
Return of ₱4,178.46, which was undisbursed upon expiration of the period covered by the Grant, to the National Treasury, or provide proof /documents that the said balance was used for COVID-related PPAs;
Municipal Planning and Development Office to prepare the respective AIP in reference to the COVID 19 Response Fund in the LDF plan and have the same be approved by the sanggunian for its authorization;
Municipal Accountant to ensure that disbursement vouchers are duly supported with the required documents that will support its validity, and facilitate the proper liquidation and recording of the BGCM grant in CY 2020 of ₱9,006,878.00 that were still recorded in the books;
Municipal Accountant to submit full details of COVID utilization for CY 2021 in the amount of ₱6,047,744.20 to support the submitted Annex C as required by the Circular, and ensure that transactions recorded and entries in the subsidiary ledger are complete with all the necessary details as to check number, particulars, date, voucher number;
Municipal Accountant to ensure that purchases like rice, medical supplies, t-shirts and aprons are recorded first as Inventory and expensed only when supported with RIS, and, for the purchases recorded above as expense, submit justification or supporting documents to support the validity of the said purchases under COVID 19 Fund whether still undispensed or already distributed to accord proper accounting thereof in the books;
Property and Inspection Officer to properly accomplish the necessary documents like Inspection and Acceptance Report, and maintain the necessary records pertaining to Property and Supplies of the LGU;
Municipal Budget Officer to review and ensure that plans forwarded to their office be attached with pertinent documents that will support its validity;
BAC Chairperson to properly plan procurement of goods and services and ensure that the mode of procurement are supportive of the normal procurement process;
Refrain from charging to COVID Fund disbursement that are not COVID related because it defeats the purpose of the fund.

We recommended that Management require the Municipal Accountant to:
Individually evaluate the balances reflected in the books, and, if found to be remaining balances, revisit the MOA or coordinate with the Source Agency to determine whether the balances have to be returned to the Source Agency, and effect the return of the same, as appropriate;
Ensure that the records of receipts of fund transfers are supported with source documents, particularly, the Memorandum of Agreement should be attached to the Journal Voucher as required under COA Circular 2012-001;
Ensure that entries in the subsidiary ledgers are consistently and properly maintained, provide adequate details on the transactions, including the beginning balances, so that sufficient information can be provided as needed by fiscal or control agencies of the government;
Effect adjusting entries in the books as to BGCM grant received in CY 2020 if fully utilized already. If not, return the same to the National Government; and
Ensure that proper control is in place as to periodic reconciliation between the GL and SL balances as well as proper posting of transactions in the SL.

We recommended that Management:
Together with the Municipal Development Council, to ensure that PPAs in the Local Development Plan are supported with the necessary in-depth study and planning documents before its inclusion in the Plan to warrant the possible attainment of the project within the year;
Require the MPDC and implementing offices to consider during their deliberation the possible limitations in the implementation of the proposed priority projects, and ensure that these projects are realizable within the year it was intended to be completed;
Direct the implementing offices to address the limitations or problems identified during the planning phase to guarantee the completion of the projects and deliver its purpose to the intended beneficiaries;
Conduct close coordination between the Implementing Office and Reporting Office together with the Budget and Accounting Office to reconcile any difference in the reports to be submitted and to substantiate and support the balances reported.
Provide reason for reporting the Municipal Electrification Program as 100 per cent complete despite its partial implementation as well as on the loan amortization status.

We recommended that Management:
Create an Inventory Committee composed of adequate number of members, which shall include at least one member each from the Office of the Municipal Accountant and Office of the Municipal Treasurer;
Require the head of various offices to oversee the conduct of physical count of existing PPEs found in their respective offices and prepare the report using Annex A of the cited Circular for verification of the Inventory Committee;
Direct the Municipal Treasurer to update the RPCPPE using the data provided by various offices to reflect the actual count and value of the PPE items maintained by the Municipality; and
Direct the Municipal Accountant to prepare and maintain PPELCs for all items of PPE and ensure that the total balance of PPELCs tally with the balances of controlling PPE accounts in the General Ledger.

We recommended that Management direct the:
The Municipal Accountant to use the accounts, Welfare Goods for Distribution, and Welfare Goods Expense, for the purchase or receipt, and issuance or distribution of relief goods, respectively; and refrain from making entries in the books of accounts without sufficient supporting documents to substantiate the transactions;
The GSO-designate to prepare and maintain the stock cards, and the Report on Supplies and Materials Issued for supplies, and fill-out completely the minimum required information on forms, such as the date on the Requisition and Issue Slip and Inspection and Acceptance Report;
The preparation of Relief Distribution Sheets, and Liquidation Reports specifying clearly on the face of the document the following information, at a minimum: (1) the appropriate document title; (2) date; (3) type/s and quantity of relief goods to be received by each beneficiary; and (4) residence of the beneficiary; and
The implementation of tighter internal control measures on inventories, particularly those held as a provision for contingencies, such as the creation of a written policy that will set a clear guideline on inventory stocking and distribution, identification of a better storage facility, or evaluation on the types and quantities of items to be stored, with consideration on the existing storage capacity of the Municipality.

We recommended that management:
Prepare a clear, comprehensive and well defined implementing guidelines on the  LGU AICs program and all other assistance and institutionalize the same to formalize its adoption to ensure that only qualified and eligible indigent beneficiaries were given the type, kind and amount of assistance they needed after the assessment, validation and recommendation of the MSWDO.
Initiate a comprehensive review of the LGUs Program on AICS and all other assistance to the poor, vulnerable and marginalized individuals and families so that the LGUs AICs and other assistance program attains its purpose and its benefits redound to as many qualified and needy clients the fund can accommodate;
Thru the MSWDO, to conduct a prior study, screening, verification, assessment and recommendation of qualified recipients of the program and install and implement a control mechanism that would monitor on the duplication of beneficiaries and assistance, qualification and eligibility of beneficiaries and funds available for disbursement;
Thru the MSWDO, to install a database encoding system  like a Crisis Intervention Monitoring system as stated in the DSWD guidelines, instead of a logbook that can easily summarize data in a particular period as well as fast checking of names of beneficiaries to avoid duplication and minimize manual errors committed in the screening and evaluation process.;
Thru the Municipal Accountant, to ensure that disbursement vouchers are attached with complete and adequate documentation to support the transactions pertaining to AICS and all other assistance before its release;
Thru the Municipal Budget Officer, to ensure that funds are available in the disbursement of AICs and other assistance without sacrificing other programs of the LGU and disbursements charged to the fund are indeed for the LGU assistance program.

We recommended that Management:
Designate a Special Disbursing Officer at the MSWDO or Treasury Office who will handle the cash advance specifically for AICS disbursement and other assistance program of the LGU.;
Instruct the MSWDO that granting of financial assistance to indigent beneficiaries be given in form or outright cash instead of individual checks under the beneficiaries name for speedy release of assistance at the earliest possible time subject to the guidelines of DSWD in case the LGU haven’t formally adopted a guidelines of their own on the range of amount given;
Formalize the payment scheme of assistance in the way that immediate delivery of service can be availed by the needy clients for the achievement of the purpose of AICs.

We recommended that Management direct the GFPS to:
Categorize correctly the GAD PPAs as either client-focused or organization-focused, and conduct the appropriate HGDG tests on the planned and implemented major programs of the LGU to determine its relevance, impact and attributable costs to GAD;
Prepare a GAD Accomplishment Report based on the GAD Plan and Budget previously reviewed and endorsed by DILG, fill out columns therein with appropriate and adequate information, and attach relevant supporting documents;
Ensure that any changes in the GPB are properly communicated to the DILG and proper procedures were followed before any changes were effected and adequate disclosure on the variance/remarks column was reflected; and
Implement a defined monitoring and evaluation system to properly assess the status and impact of GAD PPAs on gender mainstreaming.

We recommended that Management:
Convene with the LSB and agree on the timeline of the preparation and approval of the SEF budget following the indicative period of relevant activities in the cited Joint Circular;
Direct the Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant to work together in the preparation of the certified statement of SEF income to properly establish a more realistic basis of the available fund for appropriation;
Require the LSB to prepare the SEF Budget using Budget Preparation Form No. 1, and present the proposed expenditures for the budget year in detail, by PAP, by allotment class and per school; and
Remind the LSB to review the budget and its components to ensure that the fund will be utilized for priority programs and projects and will be prepared in accordance with the requirements of the relevant laws, and regulations.

We recommended that Management:
Direct the Environmental Management Specialist to review and update annually the provisions of the 10-Year Ecological Solid Waste Management Plan, and ensure compliance to the requirements of the DENR-EMB V to facilitate its  prompt approval and implementation;
Submit a copy of the Executive Order on the establishment of a MSWMB, if already existing; otherwise, create a MSWMB which shall be composed of members from associations or sectors cited in Section 12 of the Act;
Coordinate with the DENR and the Environment Management Bureau for possible solution or alternatives for the final disposal of their residual wastes, taking into consideration the absence of suitable site for a sanitary landfill in the Municipality; and
Work closely with the officials of the barangays to ensure that the Municipal policies on solid waste management are properly communicated and implemented at the barangay level to ensure that their solid waste management practice are supportive of the LGU.

We recommended that Management require the:

Present Municipal Treasurer to monitor all cash transactions and to periodically reconcile its records with the Accounting Department to ensure that all collections, deposits and adjustments are properly accounted and recorded; 

Municipal Accountant to coordinate with the Municipal Treasurer to account the disposition of reconciling items in the Bank Reconciliation Statement;
Municipal Accountant to review its records and make corresponding entries to record any unrecorded transactions or adjustments to properly reflect the correct cash balance in the books; and

Former Municipal Treasurer to deposit her undeposited collections totaling ₱189,517.54.

We recommended that Management:

require employees/officials still in the service to settle all unliquidated cash advances;

send final demand letters to persons not anymore connected with the LGU to settle the balance of their cash advances;

request write-off of unliquidated balances of deceased accountable officers in accordance with COA Circular 2016-005; and

ensure that the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances be in accordance with the provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002.

We recommended that the LGU, through the Municipal Mayor:

Be cautious in entering into agreements concerning parcels of land by ensuring that the seller is the absolute owner of the property to avoid issues on ownership and possession in the future;

Refrain from purchasing parcels of land that has encumbrances, or in other words, purchase parcels of land with clean titles;

Properly plan a proposed loan, such that only those that are actually needed by the LGU are included; 

Submit to the Audit Team a copy of the Memorandum of Agreement with the DAR concerning the BUB Project on the procurement of land for various programs, plans, and activities of the LGU; 

Ensure that all expenditures of the LGU is backed up by adequate and specific appropriation;

Abort from the agreement and rescind the Deed of Conditional Sale entered into with the Seller for being void and contrary to law, inasmuch as the Deed of Absolute Sale transferring to her the parcels of land owned by the Absolute Owner by virtue of P.D. No. 27 was void; and

Recover the amount partially paid for the purchase of the lot.

We recommended that Management direct the Municipal Assessor to:

discontinue adopting the stripping method of assessment in determining the value of commercial lots as provided for in the Manual on Real Property Appraisal and Assessment Operations;

update the Field Appraisal and Assessment Sheets (FAASs) of those properties in which FAASs remain to be not updated for a long period of time, even when there exists no transaction;

make sure that the fair market values of the real properties, including the improvements, are properly reflected in the tax declarations and FAASs;

conduct actual inspection of real properties whenever doubt arises as to the sworn statement filed by the declarant as to the true value of their property;

prepare a complete copy of the Assessment Rolls in order to properly account for the real properties located in the Municipality; and

coordinate and follow up with the Provincial Government of Camarines Sur as to the status of enforcement of the General Revision, in order to avoid the lax imposition of the supposedly increase in tax collections.

We recommended that Management:
require employees/officials still in the service to settle all unliquidated cash advances;
send final demand letters to persons not anymore connected with the LGU to settle the balance of their cash advances;
request write-off of unliquidated balances of deceased accountable officers in accordance with COA Circular 2016-005; and
ensure that the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances be in accordance with the provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002.

We recommended that the LGU, through the Municipal Mayor:
Be cautious in entering into agreements concerning parcels of land by ensuring that the seller is the absolute owner of the property to avoid issues on ownership and possession in the future;
Refrain from purchasing parcels of land that has encumbrances, or in other words, purchase parcels of land with clean titles;
Properly plan a proposed loan, such that only those that are actually needed by the LGU are included;
Submit to the Audit Team a copy of the Memorandum of Agreement with the DAR concerning the BUB Project on the procurement of land for various programs, plans, and activities of the LGU;
Ensure that all expenditures of the LGU is backed up by adequate and specific appropriation;
Abort from the agreement and rescind the Deed of Conditional Sale  entered into with the Seller for being void and contrary to law, inasmuch as the Deed of Absolute Sale transferring to her the parcels of land owned by the Absolute Owner by virtue of P.D. No. 27 was void; and
Recover the amount partially paid for the purchase of the lot.

We recommended that Management:
stop the granting of additional cash advances to Accountable Officers and officials/employees unless the previous ones are fully settled;
require employees/officials still in the service to settle all unliquidated cash advances;
send final demand letters to persons not anymore connected with the LGU for their unsettled cash advances;
request write-off of unliquidated balances of deceased accountable officers; and
ensure that the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances shall be in accordance with the provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002.

We recommended that Management:
stop granting of additional cash advances to Accountable Officers and employees unless the previous ones are fully settled;
institute the appropriate legal actions/sanctions against those erring accountable officers/employees for continued non-compliance with the existing laws, rules and regulations on the granting, utilization of cash advances, if warranted;
ensure that the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances is in accordance with the provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002; and
reclassify the cash advance balances under Advances to Officers and Employees, not pertaining to travel, to its proper accounts in consonance with COA Circular 2015-009.

We recommended that Management direct the Municipal Accountant to:
avoid the setting up of payables on services not yet rendered for infrastructure assets which are chargeable against funds under continuing appropriations;
strictly follow the provisions and guidelines set forth in the recording of Accounts Payable under PPSAS 19 and COA Circular 2015-009.

We recommended that Management direct the Municipal Accountant to:
require the reversion of the ₱379,965.20 to the General Fund pertaining to the unexpended balance of prior years’ DRRMF for re-appropriation;
monitor the fund and use it for purposes determined by the law;
update, reconcile and review its records to properly reflect the correct DRRM Fund in the Trust Fund; and
strictly conform to the guidelines and relevant rulings concerning the appropriation, utilization and recording of the DRRM Fund.

We recommended that Management direct the Municipal Assessor to:
discontinue adopting the stripping method of assessment in determining the value of commercial lots as provided for in the Manual on Real Property Appraisal and Assessment Operations;
update the Field Appraisal and Assessment Sheets (FAASs) of those properties in which FAASs remain to be not updated for a long period of time, even when there exists no transaction;
make sure that the fair market values of the real properties, including the improvements, are properly reflected in the tax declarations and FAASs;
conduct actual inspection of real properties whenever doubt arises as to the sworn statement filed by the declarant as to the true value of their property;
prepare a complete copy of the Assessment Rolls in order to properly account for the real properties located in the Municipality; and
coordinate and follow up with the Provincial Government of Camarines Sur as to the status of enforcement of the General Revision, in order to avoid the lax imposition of the supposedly increase in tax collections.

We recommended that Management direct the Municipal Treasurer: 
to submit to the Municipal Accountant 19 DVs totaling ₱219,060.86 who shall submit it to COA for audit to forestall the issuance of Notice of Suspension; 

for internal control purposes, stop the practice of allowing claimants to have possession of paid Disbursement Vouchers to prevent misplacement of the same, and if it could not be avoided, monitor the timely return of said vouchers.

We recommended that Management:
(a.) refrain from granting additional cash advances to officers and employees unless the previous cash advances are liquidated;
(b) demand immediate liquidation of all unsettled cash advances, specifically the substantial amount of prior years’ balances, in accordance  with  the provisions of . COA Circular 97-002;
(c) intensify the regular - monitoring  of granting, utilization and settlement of all cash advances; and
(d) -enforce the implementation of the _provision in the withholding of salary for officer and employees and cash advances as provided by the above circulars.
